provider.description:
The provider type for the kops package. By default, resources use package-wide configuration
settings, however an explicit `Provider` instance may be created and passed during resource
construction to achieve fine-grained programmatic control over provider settings. See the
[documentation](https://www.pulumi.com/docs/reference/programming-model/#providers) for more information.

kops:index/cluster:Cluster.description:
## Import

You can import an existing cluster by creating a `kops_cluster` configuration

```sh
 $ pulumi import kops:index/cluster:Cluster and running the `terraform import` command
```

 1. Create a terraform configuration:



 hcl



 provider "kops" {





 state_store = "s3://cluster.example.com"



 }



 resource "kops_cluster" "cluster" {





 name







= "cluster.example.com"





 // ....



 }

```sh
 $ pulumi import kops:index/cluster:Cluster

Run `terraform import`
```



```sh
 $ pulumi import kops:index/cluster:Cluster kops_cluster.cluster cluster.example.com
```

additionalNetworkCidrs.description:
- List(String) - AdditionalNetworkCIDRs is a list of additional CIDR used for the AWS VPC
or otherwise allocated to k8s. This is a real CIDR, not the internal k8s network
On AWS, it maps to any additional CIDRs added to a VPC.

additionalPolicies.description: - Map(String) - Additional policies to add for roles.

additionalSans.description: - List(String) - AdditionalSANs adds additional Subject Alternate Names to apiserver cert that kops generates.

addons.description: - List(addon_spec) - Additional addons that should be installed on the cluster.

adminSshKey.description: - (Sensitive) - String - AdminSshKey defines the cluster admin ssh key.

api.description: - access_spec - API field controls how the API is exposed outside the cluster.

assets.description: - assets - Assets is alternative locations for files and containers; the API under construction, will remove this comment once this API is fully functional.

authentication.description: - authentication_spec - Authentication field controls how the cluster is configured for authentication.

authorization.description: - authorization_spec - Authorization field controls how the cluster is configured for authorization.

awsLoadBalancerController.description: - aws_load_balancer_controller_config - AWSLoadbalancerControllerConfig determines the AWS LB controller configuration.

certManager.description: - cert_manager_config - CertManager determines the metrics server configuration.

channel.description: - String - The Channel we are following.

cloudLabels.description: - Map(String) - CloudLabels defines additional tags or labels on cloud provider resources.

cloudProvider.description: - String - The CloudProvider to use (aws or gce).

clusterAutoscaler.description: - cluster_autoscaler_config - ClusterAutoscaler defines the cluster autoscaler configuration.

clusterDnsDomain.description: - String - ClusterDNSDomain is the suffix we use for internal DNS names (normally cluster.local).

configBase.description:
- (Computed) - String - ConfigBase is the path where we store configuration for the cluster
This might be different than the location where the cluster spec itself is stored,
both because this must be accessible to the cluster,
and because it might be on a different cloud or storage system (etcd vs S3).

configStore.description: - String - ConfigStore is the VFS path to where the configuration (Cluster, InstanceGroups etc) is stored.

containerRuntime.description: - String - Container runtime to use for Kubernetes.

disableSubnetTags.description: - Bool - DisableSubnetTags controls if subnets are tagged in AWS.

dnsZone.description:
- String - DNSZone is the DNS zone we should use when configuring DNS
This is because some clouds let us define a managed zone foo.bar, and then have
kubernetes.dev.foo.bar, without needing to define dev.foo.bar as a hosted zone.
DNSZone will probably be a suffix of the MasterPublicName and MasterInternalName
Note that DNSZone can either by the host name of the zone (containing dots),
or can be an identifier for the zone.

egressProxy.description: - egress_proxy_spec - HTTPProxy defines connection information to support use of a private cluster behind an forward HTTP Proxy.

encryptionConfig.description: - Bool - EncryptionConfig controls if encryption is enabled.

etcdClusters.description: - List(etcd_cluster_spec) - EtcdClusters stores the configuration for each cluster.

externalPolicies.description: - Map(List(String)) - ExternalPolicies allows the insertion of pre-existing managed policies on IG Roles.

fileAssets.description: - List(file_asset_spec) - A collection of files assets for deployed cluster wide.

hooks.description: - List(hook_spec) - Hooks for custom actions e.g. on first installation.

iam.description: - (Computed) - iam_spec - IAM field adds control over the IAM security policies applied to resources.

isolateMasters.description:
- Bool - IsolateMasters determines whether we should lock down masters so that they are not on the pod network.
true is the kube-up behaviour, but it is very surprising: it means that daemonsets only work on the master
if they have hostNetwork=true.
false is now the default, and it will:
* give the master a normal PodCIDR
* run kube-proxy on the master
* enable debugging handlers on the master, so kubectl logs works.

- topology_spec - Topology defines the type of network topology to use on the cluster - default public

- String - UpdatePolicy determines the policy for applying upgrades automatically.

kops:index/instanceGroup:InstanceGroup.description:
## Import

You can import an existing cluster by creating a `kops_instance_group` configuration

```sh
 $ pulumi import kops:index/instanceGroup:InstanceGroup and running the `terraform import` command
```

 1. Create a terraform configuration:



 hcl



 provider "kops" {





 state_store = "s3://cluster.example.com"



 }



 resource "kops_instance_group" "ig-0" {





 cluster_name = "cluster.example.com"





 name







 = "ig-0"





 // ....



 }

```sh
 $ pulumi import kops:index/instanceGroup:InstanceGroup

Run `terraform import`
```



```sh
 $ pulumi import kops:index/instanceGroup:InstanceGroup kops_instance_group.ig-0 cluster.example.com/ig-0
```

 ~> The id of the instance group to be imported must be given in the

`cluster name/instance group name` format.

## # kops.getClusterStatus

Provides a kOps cluster status data source.

This data source assumes the cluster has been applied (or updated) see [kops.ClusterUpdater](https://www.terraform.io/docs/resources/cluster_updater).
